## Context
Built on the expanded v2.0 corpus (ticket 0013). Not a methods paper. Not a
"we should include more languages" paper. An empirical finding about whose
evidence shapes climate policy.

Core argument: the $300 billion NCQG was constructed using evidence from one
linguistic tradition. Chinese climate finance scholarship — from the world's
largest developing-country emitter and South-South financier — was invisible
to the process. Here's what it says. Here's what was missed.

This is the paper that gets 30+ cites because every future climate finance
review has to engage with it.

## Framing (not methods, not advocacy)
- Lead with the finding: "X% of global climate finance scholarship is
  invisible to English-language reviews"
- Show what's in the invisible part: specific Chinese traditions (South-South
  cooperation, Belt-and-Road climate framing), Brazilian traditions
  (deforestation finance, development economics)
- The two-axis design (language x geography) disentangles linguistic from
  epistemic barriers
- Policy implication: the evidence base for climate finance governance is
  structurally incomplete

## Target venues (high visibility, large citing community)
- Global Environmental Change (IF ~10, policy + social science audience)
- World Development (IF ~5, development audience)
- Nature Climate Change Analysis (IF ~30, short format, brutal acceptance)
- Environmental Research Letters (IF ~6, open access)

## Actions (sub-tickets to be created)
1. Run multilingual analysis on v2.0 corpus
2. Validate bge-m3 cross-lingual quality (ticket 0011, rebase on v2.0)
3. Identify 5-10 specific non-English works/traditions as qualitative depth
4. Citation directionality analysis with manual validation sample
5. Draft 6,000-8,000 word paper
6. Internal review (simulated peer panel)
7. Submit

## Test
Draft passes the "so what?" test: a climate finance policymaker reads it and
changes how they search for evidence.

## Exit criteria
Paper submitted to a venue with IF > 5.
